var e=`# CHAPTER 4 — Brawler 142536

The dark wasn't gradual.

It was like a light going out.

Kim lost all reference of body, weight, ground. His muscles didn't respond because there were no muscles to respond with. The darkness wasn't empty. It was dense, present, like being submerged in something that wasn't water.

*Alright. So this is it.*

— You are in a state of neural suspension. — Female voice, synthetic, absolutely calm. — This is a standard transition process before full immersion. Please remain relaxed.

*Relaxed. Sure. I'm floating in nothing, in the ether, what are my other options? Activating chill mode.*

— Verification complete. You are a new user. You will need to create your avatar. Please state your name.

— Kim.

— Age?

— Seventeen.

— Origin?

— Bravara. Marelia. If you need the zip code... I don't have it memorized.

A half-second pause. Kim felt she didn't appreciate the sarcasm.

— Welcome to the world of Illusion Fight, Kim.

The avatar materialized in front of him like a reflection that gained volume. It was him, every detail — the scars on his hands, the cap, the slight forward lean in his posture. Above the avatar's head, in pulsing orange letters, floated the username.

*Brawler 142536*

Kim stared at it for a long second.

---

The floor disappeared.

Kim was launched without warning, the digital sky opening beneath him in crimson red. Golden clouds streaked past in fast bands, towers curving into spirals like giant DNA structures, entire cities floating in slow orbit. The virtual wind hit his face with pressure his lungs could feel even without any explanation for why.

*Jack always said you could feel things in here. It really is hard to tell these sensations from the real ones. Can you actually feel pain in here?*

The arena grew beneath him. A colosseum expanding by the second, the stands materializing in layers, thousands of avatars that were catalogues of fantasy pushed to the limit.

Kim swept the rows with his eyes as he fell.

Found green dreads.

Jack was in the front row with the body of a digital werewolf and his unmistakable face, wearing the expression of someone who had expected to see an epic avatar and was processing the fact that he had bet money on the normal, everyday version of his own friend. Above his head: *Jack Dawg 987654321*.

*Is that cash? You can bet actual cash in here?*

The ground arrived.

The impact traveled up through his feet, his knees, his spine. The surface deformed around the point of contact. There was no pain. There was sensation, which was different but no less real.

Kim stayed on all fours for a second. Got up. Looked at his own hands.

Everyone had some wild, sick visual in this game except him. Huh.

---

The figure that emerged from the center of the arena was not human and made no attempt to seem like it.

Limbs too long for the proportion of its torso, eyes that were bottomless holes, silver hair contrasting with streaks that fell over its shoulders like something alive. The suit was an abomination of elegance, purple bleeding into metallic green. In its skeletal hands, a weapon-microphone of polished bone and dark metal.

The creature raised the microphone and the crowd exploded.

— Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to Illusion Fight! On the left, our brave newcomer, Brawler 142536! An immaculate record of zero wins and zero losses. As the veterans say: zero losses beats a thousand regrets. We sincerely hope he invested in good health insurance! On the right, a legend! The fearsome Electric Flash, Thunderbolt the Destroyer! One thousand two hundred and one wins, three hundred and five losses, ranked 30,156 in the SDR! BEEEETS ARE NOWWW OPEEEEEN!

The arena split into colors. An overwhelming wave of electric blue dominated the stands, nearly unanimous. A small island of a different color marked those who had bet on the underdog.

Jack was on the island. With the expression of someone beginning to question their decisions.

Kim turned his eyes to the opposite side of the arena.

What stood there was no longer the Freddy who had trembled behind a concrete column in the annex. The silver armor pulsed with accumulated energy, electric discharges snaking through the joints like veins of blue light. The helmet had an electric stripe running across the top and disappearing behind the shoulders. The visor slots glowed a vivid red.

The spear in his hands vibrated at a frequency Kim could almost feel in his chest from across the arena.

*Looks like the little mouse got himself a Goliath costume. Gotta admit, the fit goes hard. But he's not the first big guy I've had to deal with.*

— Bets are closed. Let the Illusion Fight begin.

The lightning left Thunderbolt's hands before Kim could register it.

---

The impact was electric and physical at the same time.

Every muscle contracted involuntarily at once, his knees buckled, and Kim was thrown against the arena barrier with a force that didn't belong in any game he had ever known. He collapsed to the ground, chest heaving out of rhythm.

**THE PAIN IS REAL.**

Not the kind of pain you describe to someone. The kind that takes up every available inch of your head and leaves room for nothing else. The taste of blood came right after, metallic and deep. The smell of singed hair was exactly what he'd always imagined it would be.

*In none of the videos Jack showed me did I see this. I saw them suffering, but I thought it was acting. These people were actually feeling pain. What kind of person plays a game to feel PAIN? Three billion people, literally choosing to suffer. What kind of INSANE world is this?*

He managed to sit up. The arena barrier was cold against his back.

Thunderbolt walked toward him with measured steps. The walk of someone who knows the result is already decided and prefers to take his time getting there.

— The famous King of School Fights can't keep his legs straight.

Kim tried to stand. His legs wavered. He made it halfway, braced against the barrier, teeth locked together.

*I'm not losing here. This isn't the first time I've felt like this, and it won't be the last. I can take it.*

— Keep talking, you piece of—

The sentence got cut off.

Thunderbolt's fist buried into Kim's stomach with force that wasn't human. All the air left at once. Kim folded. The rising kick came before he reached the ground, connected with his back, and Kim went down a second time with nothing left to stop the fall.

Thunderbolt placed one foot on Kim's back and turned to face the crowd.

— Sorry, were you saying something? This is IF, baby. This is what you're all here for, isn't it?

The crowd roared.

Kim felt the weight of that foot on his back and heard everything with his face pressed against the arena floor.

*WHAT THE HELL. This isn't a game, this is a gladiator pit. Insane. Completely insane. I need to at least land one punch on this guy.*

Thunderbolt crouched down and pinched Kim's right hand between two fingers. The pressure started low and climbed steadily, without stopping.

The crack of the pinky cut through the air.

Kim bit down on his lower lip until it bled. He wasn't giving Thunderbolt the satisfaction of a scream. But Thunderbolt pushed harder, the fractured fingers compressed with even more force.

*You son of a b\\*\\*\\*. I will end you. I will make you hurt.*

Consciousness started to fragment at the edges.

*Damn Jack. He's second on the list.*

Thunderbolt released the fingers, grabbed Kim by the throat, and lifted him off the ground. His body hung there, legs kicking at nothing. With his free hand, Thunderbolt delivered a backhand that connected with Kim's face with a crack that carried across the entire arena.

The crowd went silent.

The sound had been different from the previous hits. More humiliating than brutal. And the crowd that had been calling for blood since the beginning went quiet at that.

Kim stopped struggling. The pain detonated across his face, but what lingered longer was something else. Deeper. Harder to name.

— NeoGuide. Task list.

— List open.

— Add: beat down, humiliate, kneel, cry, and beg.

— Items added.

— Mark beat down and humiliate as complete.

— Items marked as complete. Next item: kneel.

— This one's going to take a while. — Thunderbolt looked at Kim with the satisfaction of someone working through a well-planned agenda. — But I'm in no rush.

In the stands, Jack's fists were clenched so tight his knuckles had gone white. The look on his face was no longer the one of someone who bet wrong.

It was something else.

Kim hung by his throat with a bloodied face, the fingers of his right hand fractured, no strength left, feeling something he had never felt before — and somewhere underneath all of it, a thought persisted with the irrationality of something that couldn't be turned off.

*Destroy this guy. Then Jack needs to pay up.*

The dark started closing in from the edges of his vision.`;export{e as default};
